<div id="review_477117236" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/477117236" />
    <a title="Roger Lohmann" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15179874-roger-lohmann"><img alt="Roger Lohmann" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1429213937p2/15179874.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/477117236?book_show_action=true">Dec 13, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roger Lohmann" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roger Lohmann" href="/user/show/15179874-roger-lohmann">Roger Lohmann</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15179874-roger-lohmann?shelf=political-philosophy">political-philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer477117236" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16566369735200855206">This book is truly a modern classic. First published around 1970, it is the fountainhead of the modern renaissance of political philosophy and theory which is still going strong four decades later. It is built around the choices Rawls believes people would make if they were behind a veil of ignorance - unable to see the consequences of their choices. This device has by itself provoked a huge response, including Robert Nozick&apos;s very interesting Anarchy, State and Utopia with its argument for at l</span>
  <span id="freeText16566369735200855206" style="display:none">This book is truly a modern classic. First published around 1970, it is the fountainhead of the modern renaissance of political philosophy and theory which is still going strong four decades later. It is built around the choices Rawls believes people would make if they were behind a veil of ignorance - unable to see the consequences of their choices. This device has by itself provoked a huge response, including Robert Nozick's very interesting Anarchy, State and Utopia with its argument for at least a minimal state. Rawls identifies two principles of justice.<br /><br />Even those who reject Rawls' argument on a variety of grounds will find some pages of deeply interesting and insightful comments, and for those who are comfortable with his fundamentally Kantian perspective and style of argumentation, moving on to his later restatements and refinements of the basic view will be very attractive. In particular, see Justice As Fairness: A Restatement.<br /><br />The influence of A Theory of Justice only continues to grow.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16566369735200855206" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
